<br>
I doubt this is popular to say, but honestly, I think for almost all people who are obese, they're obese because of lifestyle choices and don't <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>have</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> to be obese.<br>
<br>
I don't think there's anything <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>wrong</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> with being fat, and I don't think it's <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>easy</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> to take the weight off, I just think it's <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>possible</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
<br>
I think if you're more willing to go into life-risking surgery than you are to change your diet and establish an exercise routine you don't need surgery, you need a therapist.<br>
<br>
Do I think that genetics cause some people to be overweight no matter what they do?  Yes.  I also think the number of people who are truly like that is so statistically small it's irrelevant.<br>
<br>
If you're comfortable being fat, more power to ya.  If you've tried changing your food &amp; exercise habits and are finding it difficult, you have my sympathies.  But if you're trying to tell me it's <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>impossible</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> for you to lose weight, and you're still knocking back fast food (especially soda), you're smoking crack.<br>
<br>
I can't believe that kid's parents were willing to allow him to have the surgery.  That kid doesn't need his stomach stapled... he needs his allowance removed, his parents making him healthy bag lunches for school, and someone making him get his ass out of the house and do some yardwork on the weekends.<br>
<br>
If my son ends up fat, and comes to me and says &quot;Dad, I want to get my stomach stapled, I hate being fat&quot;, I'll be glad to help him change his lifestyle, or help him accept the fact that he's fat, but I'm not ever gonna support him risking his life to cut off some pounds.<br>
<br>
In fact, I think it's a parents responsibility to help make sure it doesn't even get to that point.  Some kids have higher metabolisms than others, so there's always gonna be some kids that are a little heavier, but if you notice that your kid is really ballooning to some abnormally unhealthy weight I think it's your job as a parent to get involved right then &amp; there... not because you want them lookin like a GQ model but because diabetes &amp; cholesterol that high etc are also life threatening.   <br>
<br>
- Syll <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=elsbetsquishytoes>elsbet squishytoes</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Grey</span><br>  Posts: 929<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/21/03 12:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=516.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Obesity</span><hr size=1> 15 percent of US kids are overweight.  That's too much.  Years and years of eating too much fast food and watching far too much TV and playing football on a video game console instead of playing it in the great outdoors.  And now we've developed the brilliant idea of suing the fast food industry for providing food that's much too fatty?  And stapling closed the stomachs of kids that aren't taught to not overeat.  I'm with ya on this, Syll.  Very very lame. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dreamsofpain>Dreams of Pain</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Dont ask...<br>
