<br>
With milk, for example, organic milk is basically from cows that walk around, eat grass, and get milked.<br>
<br>
Non-organic milk is from cows that are given hormones which increases their milk supply.  Their udders swell so badly that they develop sores so they're also given antibiotics.  They may or may not walk around depending on the farm (some are grass fed, some are fed cow feed which may or may not include ground up parts of other cows etc).<br>
<br>
Our country could very easily sustain an all-organic production if demand called for it.  Right now though, the demand isn't there.  If you go generic, you can get a gallon of non-organic milk for about $1.00 - $1.50.  A <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>half</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->-gallon of organic milk will cost you $2.50 - $3.00.  People on the whole don't see enough risk associated w/ non-organic foods to offset that price difference.<br>
<br>
The organic food industry is having 2 big problems right now also.<br>
<br>
1) Non-organic food producers lobbying to be able to label their food as organic.  As an example, South american countries can call their tuna &quot;Dolphin Safe&quot; even though it's not dolphin safe at all.  They claimed to WTO that it's unfair advantage for wealthier countries, because they can't afford dolphin-safe harvesting methods, and so WTO lets them call their dolphin safe when it definately isn't.<br>
<br>
2) Genetic Drift: Genetically Modified foods are living organisms, and as such reproduce.  Many species, particularly wind pollinators, can travel several miles and set up shop in neighbouring farms.  An organic corn can get &quot;infected&quot; with GM corn, and they wouldn't know it until harvest time.  You can't have <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>any</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> GM in your crops to label it organic, and so if even 1 GM stalk was growing in your crop, it means you can't call your stuff organic, and thus you can't sell it for the higher price that organic crops fetch, and you're basically screwed (because you invested all that money in organic growing methods).<br>
<br>
- Syll<br>
